Reasoning: We inspected the workbook and found a single SUMIF formula in cell B13:
`=SUMIF($I$4:$I$10,"*"&A13&"*",$B$4:$B$10)`.
The instruction asks to sum values from column B only when the corresponding cell in column I contains the text from A13 **and** does not contain any numbers.  
To achieve the “no numbers” condition we can use `SUMIFS` with multiple exclusion criteria for each digit (0‑9). LibreOffice supports `SUMIFS` and wildcard patterns, so the following formula works:

```
=SUMIFS($B$4:$B$10,
        $I$4:$I$10,"*"&A13&"*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*0*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*1*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*2*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*3*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*4*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*5*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*6*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*7*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*8*",
        $I$4:$I$10,"<>*9*")
```

We will replace the existing formula in B13 with this new one, then save the workbook to the output directory.
Code:
```repl
import openpyxl
from pathlib import Path

# Paths
input_path = Path("/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_42181_init.xlsx")
output_dir = Path("/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet")
output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
output_path = output_dir / "1_42181_init.xlsx"

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = openpyxl.load_workbook(input_path, data_only=False)
ws = wb.active  # only one sheet

# New SUMIFS formula that excludes any digits in column I
new_formula = (
    "=SUMIFS($B$4:$B$10,"
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"*\"&A13&\"*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*0*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*1*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*2*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*3*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*4*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*5*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*6*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*7*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*8*\","
    "$I$4:$I$10,\"<>*9*\""
    ")"
)

# Replace formula in B13
ws["B13"].value = new_formula

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Verify that the cell now contains the new formula
print("B13 new formula:", ws["B13"].value)
```
